WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.120 --> 00:00:03.900
Okay, so welcome to this session on stress

2
00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:05.640
across scale in cancer.

3
00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:11.060
We are going to try to be very ambitious and cover

4
00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:14.920
stress all the way across from the population level

5
00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:19.560
to the organism level, to the tissue level, and to the

6
00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:23.660
cellular and molecular level. And I think this really highlights

7
00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:27.620
that stress represents different things across the

8
00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.420
scale of stress. At the population

9
00:00:31.460 --> 00:00:34.740
level, we are thinking about stresses and

10
00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:36.730
survivorship and

11
00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:40.300
inequity.

12
00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:44.480
Then at the organism level, it's a lot about the stress

13
00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:48.260
hormones, glucocorticoids, catecholamines, and how these

14
00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.100
systemic stress responses, neuroendocrine signaling, and the

15
00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:54.740
immune system is being modulated by stress.

16
00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.180
And then these factors, of course, are affecting the tissue level with the

17
00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:02.720
cells, the immune cells that infiltrate the blood vessels,

18
00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:07.460
the extracellular matrix, metabolism in tissues,

19
00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:11.860
and that, again, affects the tissues as the

20
00:01:12.340 --> 00:01:15.760
cancer cells, the host cells that are responding to the different

21
00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:19.740
stress in different ways. So we are going to

22
00:01:19.780 --> 00:01:22.080
try to cover all of this in three talks.

23
00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:24.000
That's going to be hard.

24
00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.980
But I think it's really critical that we are thinking across

25
00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:32.760
scale. Just as an example, some of the work I've

26
00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.300
done, we had to think about how stress

27
00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:40.340
is affecting the patients, how the patients get affected by stress,

28
00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:43.920
how that leads to upregulation in stress hormones

29
00:01:44.060 --> 00:01:47.880
affecting specific immune cells and fibroblasts and extracellular matrix.

30
00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:51.880
And of course, that's mediated by effects on

31
00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:56.000
the gene expression and the metabolic

32
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.980
reprogramming of the cells. So no one person, I think, can

33
00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:04.720
really cover all of that. I think it's critical that we

34
00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.980
speak to each other across disciplines to try to

35
00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:12.020
help understand how stress is regulating cancer.

36
00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:13.420
So,

37
00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:18.380
we have selected three speakers for this talk, trying to cross

38
00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:21.900
around from the molecules to the cells.

39
00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:26.640
First, Ruth Shoresh-Jal from the Weizmann Institute will

40
00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:30.360
talk about stress and mutation dependency, so cover

41
00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:32.060
cells and microenvironment.

42
00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:36.840
I will speak next about how chronic stress affect the systemic

43
00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:41.020
immune response and the remodeling of tissues.

44
00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:45.080
And we will end with Jesse Plaschak that will talk about

45
00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:49.549
biomarkers in cancer survivors, and how they're responding to

46
00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:53.080
stress. And hopefully this will all make sense and come together.

47
00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:57.880
So with that, I'd like to invite Ruth to the

48
00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:01.820
podium to start us in the smallest of the scales.

49
00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:08.540
Thank you.

50
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.960
Okay. So, thanks everyone for

51
00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:21.080
coming. Thanks, Mikala, for inviting me to this session.

52
00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:25.049
I'm really excited to be here, because this session really

53
00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:28.820
combines the two loves in my science, the tumor

54
00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:31.460
microenvironment, and stress responses.

55
00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:35.480
And so in my lab, as Mikala mentioned, we

56
00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:38.720
are interested in stress responses in the tumor microenvironment.

57
00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:43.420
And we view tumors as ecosystems in which the cancer

58
00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:46.940
cells constantly interact with different cell types in the tumor

59
00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:50.520
microenvironment, and it is through these interactions that tumors

60
00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:53.480
progress and metastasize. And

61
00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:58.210
one really fundamental question that I find intriguing, and

62
00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:02.180
I've been looking at this since I started my lab about a decade

63
00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:06.160
ago, is understanding really how are tumor microenvironments

64
00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:10.040
created. So what makes a normal organ become a tumor

65
00:04:10.100 --> 00:04:13.920
microenvironment? And I find this interesting because the tumor

66
00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:17.280
microenvironment is considered to be genomically stable.

67
00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:21.430
So unlike the cancer cells where there are many mutations,

68
00:04:21.541 --> 00:04:25.200
this cannot be explained by mutations, but it should be

69
00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:29.080
explained by other processes. And coming at it from

70
00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:30.800
a evolutionary

71
00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:35.620
perspective and studying stress responses and thinking about

72
00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:39.460
stress responses and how they affect every process

73
00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:42.420
in the environment,

74
00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:46.840
we think that this is done, so this rewiring of the tumor

75
00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.880
microenvironment is done by a combination of signals from

76
00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:54.880
the mutated cancer cells as well as stress responses in

77
00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:56.240
the tumor microenvironment.

78
00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:00.540
So why stress responses? Tumors are stressful

79
00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:04.300
environments, so all of these different pathways highlighted

80
00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:08.300
here have been shown to play a role in the tumor microenvironment, and these

81
00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:11.760
are some more molecular examples for how stress

82
00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:15.500
responses mediate interactions between cells in the tumor

83
00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:18.500
microenvironment, and this is already quite outdated.

84
00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:21.920
This is from a review we wrote several years ago,

85
00:05:22.380 --> 00:05:25.920
showing really how stress responses mediate interactions in the

86
00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:30.060
multicellular level between cells in the microenvironment.

87
00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:34.360
So the cells that we are most interested in in the tumor

88
00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:38.140
microenvironment are cancer-associated fibroblasts or CAFs,

89
00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:42.540
and CAFs are the most abundant constituents of various carcinomas.

90
00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:46.820
Like other cells in the microenvironment, they're considered to be genomically

91
00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:50.740
stable, so not rewired to become cancer-associated

92
00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:54.220
fibroblasts through mutations, but through other processes that we try to

93
00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:58.240
understand. And CAFs are heterogeneous at many different

94
00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:02.220
levels. So they're heterogeneous in their origin, they're heterogeneous in

95
00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:05.410
their transcriptional program, and they're heterogeneous in their

96
00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:09.360
functions.And many subsets

97
00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:12.180
of CAFs were introduced over the years.

98
00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:14.700
We can kind of globally

99
00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:19.020
diversify them into

100
00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:23.100
myofibroblastic CAFs or myCAFs, which perform ECM

101
00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:24.280
remodeling functions,

102
00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:28.860
inflammatory or immune regulatory CAFs or iCAFs in short,

103
00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:32.240
which mediate responses with the immune microenvironment.

104
00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:36.680
Several years ago, our lab and others also showed that there are these

105
00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:40.200
antigen-presenting CAFs or MHC class II expressing CAFs.

106
00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:42.640
We are not really sure about their roles.

107
00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:46.580
And then other subsets were introduced, for example, these

108
00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:50.780
cancer-associated parasites or vascular-associated CAFs

109
00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:53.740
that are important for interactions with the

110
00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:57.129
vasculature. And so there are many different

111
00:06:58.420 --> 00:07:02.360
functions, many different transcriptional programs, and we also know that

112
00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:06.340
there are many different locations of fibroblasts within the tumor

113
00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:10.330
microenvironment, and I'm excited to share this slide from a review that

114
00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:13.660
Mara Sherman and I wrote together and just came online today.

115
00:07:13.800 --> 00:07:16.720
So please check it out in Nature Cancer.

116
00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:20.400
And, what we try to highlight here is that different CAF

117
00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:24.240
subsets can be localized in different parts of the tumor.

118
00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:28.180
So some of them are really cancer cell adjacent, some of

119
00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:31.060
them are more in the periphery or perivasculature

120
00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.760
region of the tumor, and some are even found in perineural or

121
00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:37.620
in tertiary lymphoid structures.

122
00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:42.420
So CAFs are heterogeneous. What we try to understand is what determines

123
00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:46.180
this heterogeneity and what will make one tumor microenvironment

124
00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:47.260
different from the other.

125
00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:49.560
And several years back,

126
00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:54.500
we showed that this is mediated in part

127
00:07:54.580 --> 00:07:58.360
by cancer mutations. So mutations in the cancer cells affect the CAF

128
00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:02.280
compositions. I show this here in breast cancer where

129
00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:05.100
we looked at two CAF subsets that at the

130
00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:09.130
time we termed pCAF and sCAF for expression of

131
00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:12.690
podoplanin and S100A4, and we found that

132
00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.860
the ratio between these two CAFs subsets is correlated with

133
00:08:16.939 --> 00:08:18.740
disease survival in the patients.

134
00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:22.600
But moreover, we found that it was correlated with mutations in

135
00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:26.610
BRCA1 and II. So BRCA mutated patients had more of

136
00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.680
these sCAFs, which are the antigen-presenting or MHC class II expressing

137
00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:34.420
CAFs, and less of these pCAFs.

138
00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:38.941
And we found that this was true not only in breast cancer, but also

139
00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:42.860
in pancreatic cancer, where we looked at the three subsets

140
00:08:42.900 --> 00:08:45.830
of CAFs, so myofibroblastic, immune regulatory, and

141
00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.160
antigen-presenting. And we found that the

142
00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:52.940
BRCA-mutated pancreatic tumors had more of

143
00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:53.760
these red,

144
00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:56.260
that you can see here hopefully,

145
00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:00.700
clusterin positive immune regulatory CAFs.

146
00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.140
So here's where we get back to stress.

147
00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:06.420
So clusterin is a chaperone, and it's known to be

148
00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:10.600
controlled by Heat Shock Factor 1, the transcriptional regulator of the heat

149
00:09:10.620 --> 00:09:11.410
shock response.

150
00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.640
And so we looked in these tumors also at the expression of

151
00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:19.520
HSF1, and we found that HSF1 as well is

152
00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:23.540
expressed more in BRCA-mutated tumors in the stroma of

153
00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:27.220
BRCA-mutated tumors than in the stroma of BRCA

154
00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:31.260
wild-type tumors. And in fact, it wasn't just HSF1, so we

155
00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:34.880
looked at other transcriptional regulators of other stress

156
00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:38.840
responses such as ATF4, and XBP1, the

157
00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.620
regulators of the ER stress response and integrated stress

158
00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:45.820
response. And we found that generally speaking,

159
00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:49.460
BRCA-mutated tumors were more stressed compared to BRCA

160
00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.380
wild-type tumors. This is again looking at the stroma.

161
00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:58.640
But BRCA-mutated tumors have mutations also in the

162
00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:02.560
stromal cells in at least one allele of BRCA, so it was important for us to

163
00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:06.380
show that this is really mediated by mutations in the cancer

164
00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:10.360
cells. And we used in vitro models and mouse models to show that

165
00:10:10.400 --> 00:10:14.020
it's really the mutations in the cancer cells that affect the fibroblasts.

166
00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:17.270
And cutting a long story short, we found that

167
00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:21.760
this environment causes the fibroblasts

168
00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:25.420
to become more immune regulatory, so more iCAF-like

169
00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:29.180
than myofibroblastic, and this is in an HSF1-dependent manner.

170
00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:33.720
So what this study showed was that the mutations in the cancer

171
00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:37.320
cells can affect the fibroblasts, rewire their transcriptional

172
00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:41.100
programs through activation of stress response

173
00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:44.900
mediated pathways through HSF1 to become

174
00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:47.880
more immune regulatory than myofibroblastic.

175
00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:52.180
And we think that this is really exciting in its potential therapeutic

176
00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:55.940
implications because we could potentially target

177
00:10:56.340 --> 00:11:00.100
these stress responses in the tumor microenvironment, and we could

178
00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:03.220
even combine this targeting with stress responses in the tumor

179
00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:06.160
microenvironment with targeting of the cancer cells.

180
00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:10.120
For example, in the context of BRCA mutations, PARP inhibitors

181
00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:13.649
are used, and this combination could be a useful

182
00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:16.820
therapeutic combination, and it could be also

183
00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:20.360
effective not only in pancreatic cancer, but across

184
00:11:20.420 --> 00:11:22.340
cancers that share these mutations.

185
00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:25.740
So in the case of BRCA mutations, we find them in

186
00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:30.100
pancreatic cancer, breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and prostate cancer.

187
00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:34.060
So this could be potentially useful across cancers, and we

188
00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:38.080
are looking into the therapeutic implications of this right now,

189
00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:39.690
and this is still unpublished.

190
00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:44.280
All right. But then we were also interested in understanding how general this

191
00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:46.340
activation of stress responses is.

192
00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:50.980
And so we took kind of a more unbiased approach where

193
00:11:51.060 --> 00:11:54.720
we looked at those four tumors that I described before, ovarian,

194
00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:58.660
pancreatic, breast, and prostate, and we looked at

195
00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:00.420
different stress response

196
00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:02.580
pathways in these

197
00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:07.300
tumors. We did this using multiplexed immunofluorescence for the

198
00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:09.820
transcription factors that are

199
00:12:10.780 --> 00:12:13.790
controlling these responses, so looking here at HSF1,

200
00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:18.160
NRF2 for the oxidative stress response, and ATF4 for

201
00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.030
the integrated stress response or ER stress response.

202
00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:25.460
And we found that generally, stromal cells that are

203
00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:29.420
close to cancer cells are more stressed than cells that are

204
00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:30.960
further away from the cancer cells.

205
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.930
So the closer you are to a cancer cell, the more stressed you

206
00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:37.976
are.But we wanted to understand this in a more kind

207
00:12:38.016 --> 00:12:41.496
of molecular transcriptional level, and so we used publicly

208
00:12:41.596 --> 00:12:45.356
available data sets, single cell RNA sequencing, publicly

209
00:12:45.376 --> 00:12:47.456
available data sets from these tumor types.

210
00:12:47.916 --> 00:12:51.796
And I'm showing this here for breast, but we did this for the other tumor types as

211
00:12:51.836 --> 00:12:55.636
well, looking at signatures of these different stress responses.

212
00:12:55.676 --> 00:12:59.256
So the heat shock response, oxidative stress response, the

213
00:13:00.136 --> 00:13:03.496
UPR, the unfolded protein response, hypoxia, and DNA

214
00:13:03.536 --> 00:13:07.225
damage. And as you can see, there are different levels of activation in

215
00:13:07.256 --> 00:13:10.966
different cell types. So there's a lot of data that I

216
00:13:10.996 --> 00:13:14.936
encourage anyone who's interested in stress responses to check out this paper,

217
00:13:15.516 --> 00:13:19.276
but just giving some bits of it. So again,

218
00:13:19.396 --> 00:13:22.696
looking here at breast cancer, we can find that, for example, the

219
00:13:22.796 --> 00:13:26.776
UPR is activated in B cells, the hypoxia stress response

220
00:13:26.816 --> 00:13:27.656
is activated in

221
00:13:29.656 --> 00:13:32.896
endothelial cells, and the DNA damage response is

222
00:13:32.976 --> 00:13:35.136
activated in immune cells.

223
00:13:35.976 --> 00:13:39.836
And we can also look at crosstalk between the different stress responses, which was

224
00:13:39.896 --> 00:13:43.516
really what we were interested in understanding, whether there's a

225
00:13:43.576 --> 00:13:47.226
network of stress responses and not just one stress response that is

226
00:13:47.296 --> 00:13:51.026
activated. And so, sorry for the quality here,

227
00:13:51.116 --> 00:13:55.096
but hopefully you can see here that, so here this

228
00:13:55.136 --> 00:13:58.996
is again breast cancer, and we can see that the heat shock response is

229
00:13:59.096 --> 00:14:02.916
coordinately regulated in different stromal cells,

230
00:14:03.316 --> 00:14:05.936
so pericytes, endothelial cells, and fibroblasts.

231
00:14:05.976 --> 00:14:09.536
The DNA damage response is activated in immune cells, as I showed you

232
00:14:09.576 --> 00:14:12.576
before, and also coordinately regulated in the

233
00:14:12.676 --> 00:14:16.536
stroma. But then when we look at the four different tumor types, we

234
00:14:16.596 --> 00:14:19.276
can find shared and unique pathways.

235
00:14:19.356 --> 00:14:22.976
So we see coordinated regulation of the DNA

236
00:14:23.056 --> 00:14:26.416
damage response in immune cells across these different tumor types.

237
00:14:26.616 --> 00:14:30.556
For example, we see the UPR activated in a coordinated

238
00:14:30.636 --> 00:14:34.496
manner only in ovarian cancer. So there's a lot of data there, and I

239
00:14:34.536 --> 00:14:38.436
encourage you to look at it, but we are interested in stromal cells,

240
00:14:38.496 --> 00:14:42.416
and so we really wanted to see what is activated in the context

241
00:14:42.476 --> 00:14:46.356
of the stroma, and this is not BRCA mutated, so HS of one

242
00:14:46.476 --> 00:14:50.196
was not the highest one here. And what we found was that in fact the

243
00:14:50.236 --> 00:14:53.836
oxidative stress response, and specifically NRF2, are

244
00:14:53.896 --> 00:14:57.236
activated in a subset of fibroblasts, but not in another.

245
00:14:57.336 --> 00:15:01.056
So in iCAFs but not myCAFs, and in a subset of

246
00:15:01.116 --> 00:15:04.916
pericytes that we termed muscle per for activation of

247
00:15:04.936 --> 00:15:08.516
pathways related to muscle functions and not

248
00:15:08.616 --> 00:15:11.316
matripair, which are more kind of ECM modulating.

249
00:15:12.416 --> 00:15:15.616
So to summarize this part, we find that

250
00:15:15.956 --> 00:15:19.396
there's a network of stress responses activated in the tumor

251
00:15:19.456 --> 00:15:23.056
microenvironment. We think that this is relevant for therapeutic

252
00:15:23.096 --> 00:15:26.936
targeting both of the oxidative stress response in the stroma,

253
00:15:27.396 --> 00:15:31.016
and of the heat shock response in the context of BRCA-mutated cancers.

254
00:15:31.696 --> 00:15:35.216
And we think that this is really a potential avenue to

255
00:15:35.316 --> 00:15:37.936
pursue therapeutically, and we are actually doing that.

256
00:15:38.496 --> 00:15:42.336
There's one more type of stress that I didn't talk about, but I'm happy to

257
00:15:42.376 --> 00:15:46.096
talk about later if anyone's interested, and that is inflammation that we are

258
00:15:46.176 --> 00:15:48.676
also looking into very extensively.

259
00:15:49.656 --> 00:15:53.456
All right, so in the last few minutes of my talk, I'd like to switch

260
00:15:53.536 --> 00:15:56.486
gears a little bit and talk about a different

261
00:15:56.916 --> 00:15:57.856
stress-related

262
00:15:58.816 --> 00:16:02.436
role of cancer-associated fibroblasts, and that is through their

263
00:16:02.496 --> 00:16:04.666
interaction with the immune microenvironment.

264
00:16:05.396 --> 00:16:08.946
So as I mentioned in the beginning of my talk, CAFs

265
00:16:09.156 --> 00:16:12.726
regulate the immune microenvironment through

266
00:16:12.836 --> 00:16:16.216
various different pathways, and we were interested in

267
00:16:16.276 --> 00:16:17.506
understanding whether

268
00:16:18.316 --> 00:16:22.266
specifically CAFs regulate NK cells, so natural killer cells.

269
00:16:23.096 --> 00:16:26.686
NK cells are cells that are supposed to deal with

270
00:16:26.796 --> 00:16:30.596
stressed cells. So they're supposed to eat stressed cells, they're

271
00:16:30.636 --> 00:16:33.976
supposed to eat cancer cells, but this doesn't always happen.

272
00:16:33.996 --> 00:16:37.796
And we were interested in understanding whether CAFs have anything to

273
00:16:37.876 --> 00:16:41.596
do with the fact that NK cells are not very active in some

274
00:16:41.636 --> 00:16:45.376
types of tumors. So what we did was to

275
00:16:45.436 --> 00:16:46.416
isolate and

276
00:16:47.236 --> 00:16:51.116
use an ex vivo model where we combine NK

277
00:16:51.175 --> 00:16:55.076
cells, CAFs from tumors, and cancer cells, in this case, for

278
00:16:55.116 --> 00:16:57.776
tumor and breast cancer, triple negative breast cancer cells.

279
00:16:58.536 --> 00:17:01.516
And what we found was that when you

280
00:17:01.576 --> 00:17:05.277
pre-incubate or expose the NK cells to CAFs

281
00:17:05.336 --> 00:17:07.456
before they meet the cancer cells,

282
00:17:08.497 --> 00:17:10.816
they cannot kill the cancer cells very efficiently.

283
00:17:10.916 --> 00:17:14.536
So these are, again, these pCAFs, these podoplanin positive CAFs, and

284
00:17:14.596 --> 00:17:16.636
compared to normal mammary fibroblasts,

285
00:17:17.676 --> 00:17:20.136
the NK cells are really inhibited by these cells.

286
00:17:21.156 --> 00:17:22.676
How is this mediated? So

287
00:17:23.116 --> 00:17:26.696
we looked at

288
00:17:26.856 --> 00:17:29.076
different receptors on the NK cells.

289
00:17:29.156 --> 00:17:32.816
They have a repertoire of activating and inhibitory

290
00:17:32.896 --> 00:17:36.656
receptors. And what we found was that the expression of two

291
00:17:36.756 --> 00:17:40.536
activating receptors, NKG2D and DNAM1, is

292
00:17:40.616 --> 00:17:44.056
inhibited when they're incubated or when they were

293
00:17:44.096 --> 00:17:48.036
exposed to CAFs compared to no exposure

294
00:17:48.076 --> 00:17:51.745
or compared to normal mammary fibroblasts, which show kind of a

295
00:17:51.776 --> 00:17:53.476
partial phenotype.

296
00:17:54.716 --> 00:17:56.876
Is this through ligand receptor interaction?

297
00:17:56.936 --> 00:18:00.876
So we looked at the ligands for these receptors on the CAFs, and

298
00:18:00.916 --> 00:18:04.396
we found that indeed, some of these ligands are

299
00:18:04.476 --> 00:18:06.896
activated or overexpressed in the CAFs,

300
00:18:07.796 --> 00:18:11.436
as shown here for CD155 and ULBP1.

301
00:18:12.336 --> 00:18:16.296
So then our hypothesis was that, so we have

302
00:18:16.356 --> 00:18:19.768
ligand receptor binding, and thenWhat happens?

303
00:18:19.798 --> 00:18:23.438
So we thought that potentially this could be internalized, the

304
00:18:23.488 --> 00:18:27.458
complex of the ligand receptor, and then the NK cells are left without these

305
00:18:27.548 --> 00:18:31.328
activating receptors. And so to look at this,

306
00:18:32.568 --> 00:18:35.928
we looked at the expression of

307
00:18:35.988 --> 00:18:39.748
the ligands and receptors on the NK cells upon

308
00:18:39.808 --> 00:18:43.768
interaction with the cancer-associated fibroblasts using ImageStream.

309
00:18:44.188 --> 00:18:47.208
So what you can see here is that when we

310
00:18:47.268 --> 00:18:49.308
have the

311
00:18:50.728 --> 00:18:54.628
NK cells here, you see DNAM1 expressed on the cell surface

312
00:18:54.708 --> 00:18:58.248
of the NK cells. But then when we add the fibroblasts

313
00:18:58.288 --> 00:19:01.828
before, when they are exposed to fibroblasts, indeed, this

314
00:19:02.328 --> 00:19:05.388
complex is internalized, and this is quantified here.

315
00:19:07.008 --> 00:19:09.648
But does this really affect the cytotoxicity?

316
00:19:09.658 --> 00:19:13.368
Do these ligand receptor interactions affect the cytotoxicity of the NK

317
00:19:13.428 --> 00:19:16.818
cells? So the answer is yes. We used inhibitory

318
00:19:18.288 --> 00:19:21.848
antibodies in order to block this interaction, and we found that indeed,

319
00:19:22.208 --> 00:19:25.588
when we block this interaction, we can partially rescue the

320
00:19:25.648 --> 00:19:26.268
phenotype.

321
00:19:27.348 --> 00:19:31.208
So what's happening here? How are the CAFs inhibiting the NK

322
00:19:31.268 --> 00:19:35.228
cells? So we thought that maybe the NK cells are eating

323
00:19:35.268 --> 00:19:38.708
the CAFs and then they are exhausted or

324
00:19:39.588 --> 00:19:41.288
cannot, for some reason,

325
00:19:42.108 --> 00:19:45.968
then attack the cancer cells. And so to test

326
00:19:46.008 --> 00:19:49.688
this, we did direct tricultures, where we mixed the

327
00:19:49.768 --> 00:19:53.568
NK cells with the fibroblasts and the cancer cells at the same time,

328
00:19:54.168 --> 00:19:57.888
and we looked at how they kill both cell types.

329
00:19:57.948 --> 00:20:00.708
So you can see this here. I'll play the movie in a second.

330
00:20:00.748 --> 00:20:04.728
And you'll see the fibroblasts in pink, the cancer cells here in green,

331
00:20:04.808 --> 00:20:08.608
and the NK cells are transparent. And what we found is that they

332
00:20:08.688 --> 00:20:12.408
kill the CAFs much faster than they kill the cancer cells.

333
00:20:13.308 --> 00:20:17.188
And this is quantified here, suggesting that it's really

334
00:20:17.208 --> 00:20:20.948
through the phagocytosis of CAFs

335
00:20:21.008 --> 00:20:24.908
that the NK cells cannot then kill the cancer

336
00:20:24.948 --> 00:20:25.288
cells.

337
00:20:26.808 --> 00:20:30.208
So this was all done with

338
00:20:30.568 --> 00:20:34.148
cells isolated from tumors, but we still wanted to see what happens

339
00:20:34.228 --> 00:20:37.888
actually in the mouse, what happens in vivo, because this was all ex vivo.

340
00:20:38.488 --> 00:20:42.368
And so to do this, we used a different cancer

341
00:20:42.448 --> 00:20:43.948
cell line, which

342
00:20:44.788 --> 00:20:48.608
we can orthotopically inject into syngeneic

343
00:20:48.628 --> 00:20:51.728
mice. But this cell line comes in two flavors.

344
00:20:51.788 --> 00:20:54.068
It's called T2A1, and it has

345
00:20:55.348 --> 00:20:58.928
a more metastatic version, which also recruits more stroma,

346
00:20:59.388 --> 00:21:02.358
as you can see here with smooth muscle actin staining.

347
00:21:02.848 --> 00:21:06.348
And so we try to look at how these tumors form

348
00:21:06.468 --> 00:21:09.928
when we inhibit or deplete NK cells in the mice.

349
00:21:10.518 --> 00:21:14.508
And what we found was that when you deplete NK cells

350
00:21:14.608 --> 00:21:18.548
in the parental strain, which is less stromal, indeed, we see much

351
00:21:18.608 --> 00:21:22.437
more stroma now, suggesting that when you don't have NK cells,

352
00:21:22.568 --> 00:21:26.088
you have much more CAFs. And we didn't see this in the more

353
00:21:26.148 --> 00:21:29.628
metastatic line, which has so many CAFs that the NK cells are probably

354
00:21:29.688 --> 00:21:32.888
overwhelmed by them, and this is quantified here.

355
00:21:33.428 --> 00:21:36.768
We also looked directly at CAF accumulation, so this is looking

356
00:21:36.888 --> 00:21:40.508
at collagen, but we also looked at CAFs directly, and we

357
00:21:40.568 --> 00:21:44.508
saw the same phenotype. And finally, we wanted to see that

358
00:21:44.588 --> 00:21:48.497
this is relevant to the human disease, and so we performed

359
00:21:48.548 --> 00:21:51.777
multiplex immunofluorescence staining of tissue

360
00:21:52.228 --> 00:21:54.388
microarray from breast cancer patients.

361
00:21:54.448 --> 00:21:58.388
And we found that expression of nectin-2

362
00:21:58.968 --> 00:22:00.488
on the fibroblasts in

363
00:22:02.168 --> 00:22:05.948
these cancer patients was correlated with poor survival, suggesting that

364
00:22:06.008 --> 00:22:06.388
indeed,

365
00:22:07.268 --> 00:22:09.388
there is an effect in patients.

366
00:22:10.188 --> 00:22:13.968
So to summarize this story, what we think is that the

367
00:22:14.028 --> 00:22:17.328
CAFs serve as decoys for the NK

368
00:22:17.368 --> 00:22:21.208
cells, so they engage the NK cells, and then the NK cells

369
00:22:21.248 --> 00:22:24.288
cannot kill the cancer cells efficiently.

370
00:22:24.348 --> 00:22:28.338
And so to sort of summarize everything I showed you today,

371
00:22:28.468 --> 00:22:31.997
we think that tumor microenvironments, or in the case of

372
00:22:32.028 --> 00:22:35.428
fibroblasts at least, they are rewired to become

373
00:22:35.448 --> 00:22:38.967
protumorigenic by a combination of signals from the mutated

374
00:22:39.048 --> 00:22:42.788
cancer cells as well as from the microenvironment, and that

375
00:22:42.888 --> 00:22:46.668
stress responses are really important in driving these

376
00:22:46.948 --> 00:22:48.148
phenotypic changes.

377
00:22:49.128 --> 00:22:52.988
And finally, I'd like to end by acknowledging the people who

