is

500
00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:52.900
well conserved between people and rodents, and that

501
00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:56.640
allowed a former postdoctoral fellow in my lab, Suyun He,

502
00:30:57.200 --> 00:31:00.800
to try to ask, using mice, how does stress affect cancer

503
00:31:00.860 --> 00:31:04.520
progression, and particularly metastasis, and how do

504
00:31:04.640 --> 00:31:08.500
these stress hormones, the glucocorticoids, affect the

505
00:31:08.680 --> 00:31:10.440
tumor immune microenvironment?

506
00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:15.820
She started by combining mouse models of cancer

507
00:31:15.860 --> 00:31:19.800
progression and metastasis with mouse models that we adapted

508
00:31:19.860 --> 00:31:23.480
from the neuroscience field on exposing mice to

509
00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:27.220
stress. So tumor cells were inoculated in a mammary fat

510
00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:30.720
pad. The tumors were allowed to grow and disseminate

511
00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:33.230
spontaneously, and then they were surgically removed.

512
00:31:33.740 --> 00:31:36.660
And then the mice was exposed to daily restraint stress.

513
00:31:37.060 --> 00:31:40.900
Literally, they are putting in Falcon tubes for two hours a day

514
00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:45.600
to stress them. In the end of the experiment, we then

515
00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:46.860
detect metastasis.

516
00:31:48.020 --> 00:31:51.560
As you can see here, what she found was that the corticosterone level, the

517
00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:55.500
glucocorticoids, were increased as we wanted to model,

518
00:31:56.020 --> 00:31:59.880
and there was also a robust metastatic burden increase

519
00:31:59.920 --> 00:32:03.900
about fourfold, but with a lot of variability in how

520
00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:04.800
they responded.

521
00:32:05.740 --> 00:32:09.460
Interestingly, and I'll get back to that at the end of the talk, we noticed that in

522
00:32:09.480 --> 00:32:13.260
the control animals, we had smaller lesions and fewer of them

523
00:32:13.300 --> 00:32:16.960
were proliferating compared to in animals exposed to

524
00:32:16.980 --> 00:32:17.780
restraint stress.

525
00:32:19.020 --> 00:32:22.660
Now, we recognize that a cancer patient is not put in a

526
00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:26.660
Falcon tube two hours a day, so we wanted to try to model

527
00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:30.720
better the kind of stress that we as patients may

528
00:32:30.740 --> 00:32:34.680
experience by using what's known as a chronic unpredictable

529
00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:36.720
mild stress model, where the

530
00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:41.660
animals are randomized to different stresses every day.

531
00:32:42.120 --> 00:32:45.900
So these might be tail pinch, noise, stroboscopic

532
00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:49.660
light, food deprivation, water deprivation, and various

533
00:32:49.780 --> 00:32:52.400
changes to the environment, to the cage environment.

534
00:32:53.440 --> 00:32:57.320
This is a very involved protocol, and to sort of

535
00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.940
combine that with the dissemination, what Suyun did in

536
00:33:00.980 --> 00:33:04.760
collaboration with Evdokia and Shanu from my collaborator, Linda

537
00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:08.430
Vanal's lab, was to now make it a little bit simpler and

538
00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:12.400
inject the cancer cells directly intravenously so they disseminated to the lung,

539
00:33:13.080 --> 00:33:14.840
and then expose them to the protocol.

540
00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:19.200
As you can see here, also with this protocol, there's an increase in corticosterone

541
00:33:19.240 --> 00:33:22.740
level. It's less. It's supposed to be a milder protocol, and the

542
00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:24.400
metastatic burden is increasing.

543
00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:26.620
So how does this work?

544
00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:31.380
What we found just using tumor-free animals was that the

545
00:33:31.700 --> 00:33:35.480
lung tissue was profoundly changed after three weeks of

546
00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:38.380
exposure to these stressors.

547
00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:42.280
So there was not just one thing but a global change.

548
00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:45.900
There was an accumulation of extracellular matrix, fibronectin.

549
00:33:46.320 --> 00:33:49.980
There was a reduction in an infiltration of T cells,

550
00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:53.960
and then there was an expansion of the infiltration of neutrophils,

551
00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:58.000
whether we measured by immunohistochemistry or by flow cytometry.

552
00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:02.960
So we really got intrigued about the infiltration of

553
00:34:03.020 --> 00:34:03.680
neutrophils.

554
00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:08.341
Neutrophils are a very intriguing cell type.

555
00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:11.781
It's actually our most abundant white blood cell,

556
00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:16.560
yet it's been pretty understudied, particularly in cancer,

557
00:34:16.620 --> 00:34:20.560
until recently. I think one of the reasons it's not been studied

558
00:34:20.620 --> 00:34:24.361
as much is they're short-lived, 12 hours to five days,

559
00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:28.140
depending on where it is in the tissue or in the blood.

560
00:34:28.200 --> 00:34:31.720
So in culture, they are pretty hard to--

561
00:34:32.200 --> 00:34:34.620
So not easy to work with.

562
00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:40.270
Since they have such a big turnover, we produce and

563
00:34:40.600 --> 00:34:44.250
then also dispose of a staggering 100

564
00:34:44.281 --> 00:34:48.100
billion neutrophils every day. Think of that as two

565
00:34:48.140 --> 00:34:51.740
neutrophils for every dollar on the NIH budget that is being

566
00:34:51.841 --> 00:34:55.301
produced every day, and we can only hope that the

567
00:34:55.720 --> 00:34:57.860
NIH budget will not be neutropenic.

568
00:34:58.820 --> 00:35:02.600
Also, for the

569
00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:06.420
neutrophils, it's now known that they have both pro and anti-tumor

570
00:35:06.460 --> 00:35:09.420
functions, just like many other immune cells in the

571
00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:13.240
microenvironment. My lab have mostly focused on the pro-tumor function,

572
00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:17.420
but there are very strong data supporting that they can also directly kill

573
00:35:17.460 --> 00:35:18.220
cancer cells.

574
00:35:19.510 --> 00:35:23.300
They have this very unique type of cell death called neutrophil extracellular

575
00:35:23.360 --> 00:35:27.060
trap formation, NET or NET formation, and by scanning

576
00:35:27.120 --> 00:35:29.200
electron microscopy, it looks like this.

577
00:35:29.340 --> 00:35:32.820
These are strings of extracellular DNA that's being expelled

578
00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:37.040
into the extracellular room, and they are decorated with

579
00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:41.000
various enzymes and proteins and, of course, nucleic acids from the

580
00:35:41.060 --> 00:35:41.680
neutrophil.

581
00:35:43.160 --> 00:35:46.560
These traps were discovered or first reported on in

582
00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:50.230
2004, and since then, there's been quite a lot of

583
00:35:50.480 --> 00:35:53.100
publications on their function in cancer.

584
00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:57.700
We now know that they are induced not just by pathogens.

585
00:35:58.220 --> 00:36:01.360
They are induced during inflammation and on, of course,

586
00:36:01.520 --> 00:36:05.000
infection. And some of the factors that induce them are bacterial

587
00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:08.320
components but also chemokines or extracellular

588
00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:11.900
vesicles. And so in a tumor microenvironment, these factors can

589
00:36:11.960 --> 00:36:14.460
come, for instance, from cancer cells directly.

590
00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:19.580
In human cancers, there's been correlation between NETs and

591
00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:23.430
tumor stage and poor prognosis across a variety of different cancers,

592
00:36:23.940 --> 00:36:27.760
and there's also now clear evidence that they may confer

593
00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:31.680
resistance to chemotherapy.Mechanistically,

594
00:36:31.760 --> 00:36:35.560
what they do in the context of metastasis is that they can induce

595
00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:39.460
migration and invasion of cancer cells, and they can help the cancer cells

596
00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:41.460
extravasate at the secondary site.

597
00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:46.410
And they also really support this metastatic niche formation,

598
00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:50.160
where they alter the microenvironment where the cancer cell will

599
00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:51.120
later take seed.

600
00:36:52.680 --> 00:36:56.660
Going back to our cancer study, what we saw was that when we looked in the

601
00:36:56.720 --> 00:37:00.640
mice that had been stressed, looked at neutrophils taken from these

602
00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:04.640
mice, and kept just a few hours ex vivo, you can

603
00:37:04.660 --> 00:37:08.360
see that they were forming a staggering extra number of neutrophils.

604
00:37:09.060 --> 00:37:12.480
Each of these arrows represent a neutrophil forming NETs, as

605
00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:13.460
quantified here.

606
00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:18.700
We found that this was directly mediated by glucocorticoids acting on the

607
00:37:18.720 --> 00:37:20.720
glucocorticoid receptor in neutrophils.

608
00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:24.720
If we use conditional knockout animals lacking the receptor

609
00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:28.550
neutrophils, there was no increase in the NET formation in these

610
00:37:28.580 --> 00:37:29.240
neutrophils.

611
00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:34.420
There was also no increase in metastasis when you

612
00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:38.300
used animals that did not have the glucocorticoid receptor in the neutrophils,

613
00:37:38.860 --> 00:37:42.640
really suggesting that the neutrophils were key, and their response to the

614
00:37:42.660 --> 00:37:44.880
glucocorticoids were key in

615
00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:49.000
promoting of metastasis. But was it the NETs?

616
00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:53.320
And so to test this, what Suyun did was that she, again, did

617
00:37:53.330 --> 00:37:57.080
the spontaneous dissemination model, allowing tumor cells to

618
00:37:57.120 --> 00:38:00.850
grow and disseminate, remove the primary tumors, exposed the

619
00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:04.800
mice to restraint stress, or did that in the context of DNase,

620
00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:08.080
a enzyme that can chop off the extracellular DNA.

621
00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:11.920
If she did that, you can see that DNase worked well.

622
00:38:11.960 --> 00:38:14.500
It reduced DNase in the plasma,

623
00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:18.780
and it reduced significantly the metastasis

624
00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:22.580
in the lungs of the stressed animals, almost back to background

625
00:38:22.590 --> 00:38:26.420
level. We think it's not one thing that the NETs are doing, but

626
00:38:26.460 --> 00:38:28.780
really a global change in the microenvironment.

627
00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:32.760
And so what you can see here is that when we stress and combine with

628
00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:36.210
DNase, extracellular matrix accumulation is also reduced,

629
00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:39.239
although not all the way to background levels.

630
00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:44.700
Now, this is all mice, and of course, we want to think about what can

631
00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:47.920
cause elevated glucocorticoid levels in patients.

632
00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:51.540
And there's a variety of different things that might cause that.

633
00:38:51.900 --> 00:38:54.480
One, of course, is when you get diagnosed with cancer.

634
00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:56.760
It is an exceptionally stressful event.

635
00:38:56.800 --> 00:38:59.520
You may wonder what's going to happen to you.

636
00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:03.540
When you're exposed to a treatment, that is stressful. Will it respond?

637
00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:05.880
And a lot of treatments are stressful in themself.

638
00:39:06.309 --> 00:39:10.220
And of course, there can be financial concerns of what is the

639
00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:11.780
cancer going to mean for your family.

640
00:39:13.460 --> 00:39:17.059
In addition, we are using glucocorticoids in the clinic.

641
00:39:17.300 --> 00:39:17.570
They're

642
00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:22.160
often used with anesthesia, they're used with chemotherapy, and

643
00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:25.400
they're used in anti-inflammatory treatment after surgery.

644
00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:29.440
So a lot of the things that the cancer patient may be treated with may involve

645
00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.820
synthetic glucocorticoid exposure.

646
00:39:33.480 --> 00:39:37.360
Interestingly, it may even be that having a tumor by itself

647
00:39:37.460 --> 00:39:41.220
is a stressor. This is a study where they looked in plasma

648
00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:44.990
from patients with pancreatic cancer, and they noted that

649
00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:48.940
there is almost a doubling in the circulating glucocorticoid levels

650
00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.760
in these cancer patients.

651
00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:55.200
So we wanted to see what does glucocorticoids do

652
00:39:55.940 --> 00:39:59.860
by themself. And we wanted now to focus really here on the

653
00:40:00.520 --> 00:40:04.440
secondary side, where

654
00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:08.440
the cancer cells are arriving. We know that for many cases,

655
00:40:09.220 --> 00:40:12.920
cancer may arrive to a secondary tissue, and then in the

656
00:40:12.980 --> 00:40:16.440
context of, for instance, breast cancer, they can be dormant for years or

657
00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.580
decades before they are awakened.

658
00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.480
I think it's not just breast cancer where this is relevant for.

659
00:40:22.760 --> 00:40:26.580
This is data from my former colleague, Doc Fearon at Cold Spring

660
00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:30.340
Harbor, who had looked in autopsies from pancreatic cancer

661
00:40:30.410 --> 00:40:33.180
patients, one of the most aggressive types of cancer.

662
00:40:33.940 --> 00:40:34.160
Yet,

663
00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:38.280
some patients do live with this cancer, and when they

664
00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:42.220
autopsies, you can see here that there are single disseminated

665
00:40:42.300 --> 00:40:45.980
cancer cells in the liver. They are positive for mutant

666
00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:49.779
p53, but negative for proliferation markers.

667
00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:54.040
So I think as we get better and better to treat aggressive cancers

668
00:40:54.120 --> 00:40:57.660
such as pancreatic cancer with a KRES inhibitor or with

669
00:40:57.780 --> 00:41:01.500
vaccines, this may actually be more important than we are

670
00:41:01.510 --> 00:41:02.360
thinking about now.

671
00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:07.660
So Doc Fearon had developed a model of disseminated

672
00:41:07.720 --> 00:41:11.660
latent pancreatic cancer, and we further, and by we, I

673
00:41:11.700 --> 00:41:14.100
mean my former graduate student, Xiao Han,

674
00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:18.910
adjusted this model, refined it. So what she's doing is

675
00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:22.610
she's taking pancreatic cancer cells expressing GFP or

676
00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:26.440
luciferase. So they're sort of model antigens that also

677
00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:27.820
allow us to follow them.

678
00:41:28.700 --> 00:41:32.300
Like Suyun had done, she is allowing these tumors to grow

679
00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:36.360
for three weeks, so an immune response can be raised against these cells.

680
00:41:36.420 --> 00:41:37.680
They're surgically removed.

681
00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:42.630
We had done them subcutaneously to get the immune response and also to avoid that

682
00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:45.500
there's any dissemination to the liver from this site.

683
00:41:46.220 --> 00:41:48.000
And then you follow by luciferase.

684
00:41:48.760 --> 00:41:52.360
You can see here that in naive animals that's injected with these

685
00:41:52.380 --> 00:41:56.340
cancer cells into the spleen, into the hepatic circulation, they're

686
00:41:56.360 --> 00:41:59.000
growing rapidly. So that is how we are normally doing

687
00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:02.700
experimental metastasis, and I think it's maybe

688
00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:06.760
underestimating how much the immune response is playing a role in

689
00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:10.620
regulating metastasis. Because in these other mice, you can see there

690
00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:13.600
is no detectable metastasis by bioluminescence.

691
00:42:14.780 --> 00:42:18.340
But when you look closely in the microscope, and again, taking

692
00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:22.320
advantage of these cells expressing mutant p53, so we can detect

693
00:42:22.360 --> 00:42:25.900
them, you can see here that by day 15, when these

694
00:42:26.140 --> 00:42:30.020
naive animals have 20% of their livers occupied

695
00:42:30.060 --> 00:42:33.584
by cancer-In the immunized mice, you cannot

696
00:42:33.624 --> 00:42:37.324
detect metastasis unless you stain for p53 and find

697
00:42:37.364 --> 00:42:41.044
these individual cancer cells localized in

698
00:42:41.104 --> 00:42:41.624
the

699
00:42:42.524 --> 00:42:42.804
liver.

700
00:42:44.744 --> 00:42:47.844
These cells, when you look closely, are almost all

701
00:42:48.044 --> 00:42:51.144
95% negative for Ki-67,

702
00:42:51.704 --> 00:42:55.474
5% are cycling. Of course, this is p53,

703
00:42:55.644 --> 00:42:59.514
so we wanted to be really sure that these were cancer cells, and

704
00:42:59.624 --> 00:43:02.984
adapted a reporter that was developed in

705
00:43:03.464 --> 00:43:06.804
Ana Correia's lab. Ana Correia is one of our new ACR

706
00:43:06.904 --> 00:43:10.864
trailblazers, and she is really fantastic, and shared this construct

707
00:43:10.944 --> 00:43:13.584
with us. So now we can look in the liver.

708
00:43:13.624 --> 00:43:17.264
This is seven days after injection of the cells into the

709
00:43:17.324 --> 00:43:20.604
hepatic circulation. You have the red

710
00:43:22.364 --> 00:43:26.204
disseminated tumor cells. You can see a single cell here and a single cell

711
00:43:26.284 --> 00:43:30.204
up here. This one is GFP positive, and it is

712
00:43:30.264 --> 00:43:34.024
around E-cadherin positive epithelial cells in the liver,

713
00:43:34.524 --> 00:43:38.104
with this one is not positive for GFP, so we think it's

714
00:43:38.144 --> 00:43:41.484
cycling. And you can see there's a lot of

715
00:43:41.504 --> 00:43:45.204
E-cadherin negative cells around it, possibly immune cells.

716
00:43:46.204 --> 00:43:49.244
If we quantify this, you can see again, like with

717
00:43:49.504 --> 00:43:53.344
p53, it's 95% of the cells that are not

718
00:43:53.364 --> 00:43:55.544
cycling, that are quiescent and dormant.

719
00:43:57.284 --> 00:44:00.724
So what happens if we expose these animals to glucocorticoids?

720
00:44:01.164 --> 00:44:04.764
We now try to model what's happening in pancreatic cancer

721
00:44:04.824 --> 00:44:05.704
patients by

722
00:44:06.704 --> 00:44:09.964
injecting these cells into the hepatic circulation and then

723
00:44:10.024 --> 00:44:13.474
exposing the mice to glucocorticoids in the drinking water,

724
00:44:13.844 --> 00:44:17.434
increasing the levels of circulating glucocorticoids with about

725
00:44:18.064 --> 00:44:18.544
twofold.

726
00:44:19.884 --> 00:44:23.104
If we do that, there is profound changes in the liver

727
00:44:23.884 --> 00:44:24.844
microenvironment.

728
00:44:25.704 --> 00:44:29.684
Here, just in percentages, you can see an expansion of the neutrophils, really

729
00:44:29.724 --> 00:44:33.464
dramatic, and a retraction of the CD8 and CD4 T

730
00:44:33.524 --> 00:44:35.904
cells, and these changes were significant.

731
00:44:36.604 --> 00:44:40.333
This is after one week. It's robust even after six weeks of continuous

732
00:44:40.424 --> 00:44:44.393
treatment. Here, after four weeks, I'm just showing you the immunohistochemistry

733
00:44:44.484 --> 00:44:48.044
where you really get a sense of how few T cells are present with the

734
00:44:48.084 --> 00:44:51.874
corticosterone, and how many myeloperoxidase positive

735
00:44:51.884 --> 00:44:55.784
neutrophils. These neutrophils are forming NET, as quantified

736
00:44:55.864 --> 00:44:59.464
here, so there's a really profound increase in NET formation also with

737
00:44:59.504 --> 00:45:01.584
glucocorticoid treatment directly.

738
00:45:03.504 --> 00:45:07.484
So, of course, we had hoped that there would, or at least expected

739
00:45:07.524 --> 00:45:11.204
that there would be metastasis, but as you can see here, these elevated

740
00:45:11.284 --> 00:45:15.264
levels of glucocorticoids and these profound

741
00:45:15.304 --> 00:45:18.953
changes in T cell and neutrophil infiltration did

742
00:45:18.984 --> 00:45:21.964
not change the outcome of the mice.

743
00:45:22.064 --> 00:45:25.324
It did not have metastasis in all the ones we've looked at so far.

744
00:45:27.304 --> 00:45:30.904
What they did have when we look closely in the microscope was that there was a

745
00:45:30.984 --> 00:45:33.864
change in the proliferation status.

746
00:45:34.284 --> 00:45:38.104
So now with corticosterone, you're starting to really see a lot more

747
